07052nam a22011055i 9783110224481DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20092009gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979731454  a97831102244817 a10.1515/97831102244812doi  a(DE-B1597)38076  a(OCoLC)642685792  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP115.4b.M85 2009eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a404/.201922204aThe Multiple Realities of Multilingualism :bPersonal Narratives and Researchers’ Perspectives /ced. by Elka Todeva, Jasone Cenoz. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Applied Linguistics [TAL] ,x1868-6362 ;v30 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is the very first collection of first-person language learning narratives that offers rich introspective data on the various processes and forces shaping the development and maintenance of multiple languages (seven and more) in a single individual. The writers are twelve multilinguals who have been influenced by quite different contextual factors and who have learned a wide range and combination of dialects and languages from both similar and very different linguistic families. The combinations explored in the narratives include some lesser-known languages that come from under-researched areas, such as the African continent, certain parts of Asia, the Middle East, and Eastern Europe. Also unique are two theoretical chapters which analyze the narrative data against the background of language development research findings within several thematic areas: multiple language learning as a complex dynamic system; the influence of bilingualism/multilingualism on the acquisition of additional languages; cross-linguistic influence; and also emotions, motivation, and identity. The aim of this juxtaposition and analysis is to allow a meaningful comparison of the extent to which etic, researcher-generated, and emic, learner-offered perspectives match or diverge, and to identify new questions that the emic data may add to research agendas. The book is an excellent resource not only for researchers but also for teachers as well as for students of language at the graduate and undergraduate level.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aMultilingualismxPsychological aspects. 0aPsycholinguistics. 0aSecond language acquisition. 4aPsycholinguistik. 4aSprachdidaktik. 4aZweitspracherwerb. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aLanguage Teaching.  aPsycholinguistics.  aSecond Language Acquisition.1 aCenoz, Jasone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCenoz, Jasone, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFantini, Alvino E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreedman, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenshaw, Hamzah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHu, Haiyan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamanga, Chimwemwe Mayinde Mystic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKowalski, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Flaherty, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPopovic, Radmila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTappe, Heike M. E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTodeva, Elka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTodeva, Elka, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTonkin, Humphrey